50|$|The Powers <b>Accounting</b> <b>Machine</b> was an {{information}} processing device {{developed in the}} early 20th century for the U.S. Census Bureau. It was then produced and marketed by the Powers <b>Accounting</b> <b>Machine</b> Company, {{an information}} technology company founded by the machine's developer. The company thrived in the early 20th century as a producer of tabulating machines. It was a predecessor to the current Unisys corporation.|$|R
50|$|James Legrand Powers (1871 - November 8, 1927) - American {{inventor}} and entrepreneur, {{the founder}} of Powers <b>Accounting</b> <b>Machine</b> Company.|$|R
50|$|The IBM World Trade Corporation marketed Computing <b>Accounting</b> <b>Machines</b> (CAM), {{variations}} {{of either the}} IBM 402 or 407 with an attached computer. CAM {{variations of}} the 407 included the IBM 421, 444, and 447.|$|E
